**Some context**

I&#39;m  making a form (using [react-final-form][1]), and spying on some of the form&#39;s state.

The library provides a React component (`FormSpy`) that lets you subscribe to changes in various parts of the form&#39;s state, and calls a callback function with only those parts of the form&#39;s state (which are never `null` or `undefined`) when the form state does change.

**A simplified version of the code in question**

    // Represents the current state of the form.
    // values is an object with each field in the form as a key
    // submitting is true if a submission is currently in progress
    type FormState = {
     values?: Object,
     submitting?: boolean,
    };
    
    // Indicate which form state changes to subscribe to
    type Subscription = {
     values?: boolean, 
     submitting?: boolean, 
    };
    
    type RenderCallback = (formState: FormState) =&gt; React.Node;
    
    // The function that is automatically called with the subscribed-to parts of the form state when something changes
    function FormSpy(subscription: Subscription, render: RenderCallback) {
     // This is available to the component
     const relevantFormState = getRelevantFormStateBySubscription(subscription);

     // Call the callback with the relevant form state
     return render(relevantFormState);
    }

…&#160;and to only subscribe to changes to the form&#39;s `values` (not `submitting` state), you can use it like this (assuming that the form has a field called &quot;email&quot; with the value &quot;test@test.xyz&quot;:

    function renderEmail = ({ values: { email }}) {
     return &lt;div&gt;{email}&lt;/div&gt;;
    }

    const theSpy = (
      &lt;FormSpy
       subscription={{ values: true }}
       renderCallback={renderEmail}
     /&gt;
    );

**My problem**

As humans reading the code, we know that `values` will be an object, because we just subscribed to `values`.

However, `values` is a `Maybe` type in the `FormState` type, so Flow forces us to check that `values` exists before accessing anything in it (in this case, picking out `email`).

This works fine, but is unnecessarily bloated:

    function renderEmail({ values }) {
       if (values == null) {
        throw new Error(&#39;This never happens because of our subscription&#39;);
       }

       return &lt;div&gt;{values.email}&lt;/div&gt;;
    }

    const theSpy = (
     &lt;FormSpy
      subscription={{ values: true }}
      renderCallback={renderEmail}
     /&gt;
    );

I could also go around the problem by putting a `// $FlowFixMe` above the line where I destructure `values`, but that also mutes all other errors on that line and doesn&#39;t solve my problem.

**My question**

Is it possible to use the object keys in the `subscription` parameter to derive a type that can be used as a parameter type for `renderCallback`, so that we don&#39;t have to perform these unnecessary null/undefined checks?

That is, given a `subscription` with `values: true`, I want to create a specialised version of `FormState` like `{ values: Object }`, rather than `{ values?: Object, submitting?: booolean }`.

The keys always always have the same name in the `subscription` and the `values`—I&#39;m not sure if that matters.

Can this be done?

